erstanding the defense market.=C2=A0
Defense is Weird
=E2=80=9CDefense is weird.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
When I asked Adam Porter-Price, Anduril=E2=80=99s Head of Corporate Develop=
ment and M&A, and Matthew Steckman, its Chief Revenue Officer, in separate =
conversations, why Anduril acquires companies, they both gave the same resp=
onse.=C2=A0
So what makes defense weird?=C2=A0
In Christian Brose=E2=80=99s recent Hoover Institute paper, Moneyball Milit=
ary [ https://substack.com/redirect/415b2910-923b-4dc2-8a39-4dccf1439cf0?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], he des=
cribes the core weirdness at the heart of defense: the Planning, Programmin=
g, Budgeting, and Execution (PPBE) system that the DoD uses to define the =
=E2=80=9Cmilitary capabilities the nation requires and how to validate, fun=
d, and ultimately procure them.=E2=80=9D Brose writes (emphasis mine):
The goal of the PPBE system, when Secretary of Defense Robert McNamara inst=
itutionalized it fully from 1961 to 1968, was not to optimize or better man=
age capitalism in matters of national defense. It was to transcend capitali=
sm altogether. It was an attempt to graft an allegedly superior, explicitly=
 Soviet-style institution onto the postwar American government, ironically =
for the purpose of competing more effectively against that Soviet adversary=
=2E=C2=A0
As Lofgren writes, =E2=80=9CIt was not hyperbole when historian Charles Rie=
s described military staff planning in 1964 to be =E2=80=98almost socialist=
 in its metaphysics.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D After all, =E2=80=9Cthe economic exp=
ert and socialist alike believed that central planning could far outstrip t=
he productive capability of uncoordinated markets.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Let that sink in. It=E2=80=99s certainly not something I appreciated. As th=
e US faces threats from two centrally-planned economies, China and Russia, =
we=E2=80=99re doing so with a system modeled on theirs instead of leaning i=
nto our capitalist advantage.
To fix that, Brose recommends splitting procurement in two: continue to use=
 PPBE for traditional platforms and weapon systems, while establishing the =
Moneyball Military, generated through market creation, for =E2=80=9Crobotic=
 vehicles of all sizes in all domains, constellations of small communicatio=
ns and intelligence satellites, and other commercially derived military sys=
tems.=E2=80=9D
While there=E2=80=99s growing support for something like Brose=E2=80=99s pr=
oposal among America=E2=80=99s military leadership, the DoD is a very large=
, slow-to-turn institution. So in the interim, Anduril wants to serve as th=
e bridge between the two approaches. It needs to play by the rules of the P=
PBE on behalf of smaller defense tech companies, like an API into DoD.=C2=
=A0
So what are the rules? Three are most relevant to understanding Anduril=E2=
=80=99s acquisitions:
Small Number of Buyers. The defense sector is a monopsony [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/71adaa64-6148-45f3-be60-7538b2198eb2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the demand-side version of a=
 monopoly in which a market in which one buyer is the major purchaser. Tech=
nically, a Prime may have 10-20 relationships across the DoD=E2=80=99s bran=
ches and agencies, and among its allies, but that=E2=80=99s a tiny number c=
ompared to a typical company=E2=80=99s client roster, and DoD sets the tone=
=2E Most of the spend they compete for=20=
comes out of the Congressionally-appro=
ved DoD budget [ https://substack.com/redirect/fe739f68-c66a-480e-abfc-2eb7=
1206cae8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ].
Sales are Punctuated, not Linear. Instead of selling to customers on their =
own schedule, defense companies compete for contracts and programs that may=
 come up once every five or ten years. Companies might work on a number of =
smaller projects to build their track record, trust, and capabilities, but =
the goal is to win big programs when they come up. =E2=80=9CThere are certa=
in barriers to entry that are very real and time-based,=E2=80=9D Porter-Pri=
ce explained.=C2=A0
Wins Can Be Massive. These programs can be absolutely enormous. The Joint S=
trike Fighter program, awarded to Lockheed Martin in 2001 to produce 2,456 =
F-35 Lightning II fighter jets through 2044, is currently estimated to cost=
 $1.7 trillion. Lockheed still owns the contract despite the fact that its =
costs have ballooned ~8x from its proposal, and because contracts are cost-=
plus, the government pays the contractor=E2=80=99s cost with a margin on to=
p, Lockheed makes more money the more over budget it is.=C2=A0
While JSF is the largest, it=E2=80=99s certainly not the only enormous prog=
ram.=C2=A0
Each year, Congress approves the Defense Budget, and it continues to grow. =
The Fiscal 2024 National Defense Authorization Act allotted an all-time hig=
h at $842 billion to the DoD, a record-setting $315 billion of which will g=
o to procurement and research and development. It=E2=80=99s worth checking =
out this 2024 Defense Budget Overview presentation [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/1e7d37be-996e-4324-b95f-915811e83dec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] if you=E2=80=99re interested in the =
details.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re spending $246.6 billion this year on Integrated Deterrence: $=
61.1 billion on Air Power, $48.1 billion on Sea Power, $13.9 billion on Lan=
d Power, $37.7 billion on Nuclear Enterprise Modernization, $29.8 billion o=
n Missile Defeat and Defense, $9.0 billion on Long-Range Fires, $13.5 billi=
on on Cyberspace, and $33.3 billion on Space and Space-Based Systems.=C2=A0=
=C2=A0
Getting more granular, this table shows the 2024 Defense Budget Request per=
 weapon system:=C2=A0
Defense is a market with essentially one customer, which buys new things in=
frequently, telegraphs what it wants to buy, and when it does buy, commits =
an absolute ton of money for a very long time. In such a market, it=E2=80=
=99s critical to be =E2=80=9Cready and geared up for a competition,=E2=80=
=9D Steckman told me. =E2=80=9CIf you win, you get a big spike. If you lose=
, you get nothing.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
But winning isn=E2=80=99t as simple as having the best technology at the be=
st price. The Defense Primes spend a relative pittance on R&D compared to l=
arge tech companies, and they sell expensive platforms that regularly come =
in multiples over budget.=C2=A0
No startup can saddle up to a competition with a fancy piece of technology =
alone and expect to win. This presents a challenge for both the DoD, which =
can=E2=80=99t always acquire the best solution for the job, and defense sta=
rtups, which can=E2=80=99t simply compete on product like traditional start=
ups can. It also presents an opportunity for a startup willing to put in th=
e time and work to do all of the other things required to win.=C2=A0
Competing as a new entrant with Prime ambitions means operating with a mix =
of long-term patience and short-term speed. To go back to our Lattice analo=
gy, the platform Anduril is patiently building at the company level is trus=
t with DoD.
Trust in Anduril as a Network Effect=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI haven=E2=80=99t listened to Brian=E2=80=99s podcast, although I=
=E2=80=99m sure it was amazing. Put that in the piece.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I was asking Steckman about the question Ben Thompson asked Anduril CEO Bri=
an Schimpf [ https://substack.com/redirect/1258dc90-a186-4b55-8abc-4a34b4ed=
0102?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] o=
n Lattice=E2=80=99s network effects, to which Schempf replied, =E2=80=9CI t=
hink as we add more platforms, more sensors, more capabilities into this, e=
verything gets more valuable, I think that=E2=80=99s spot on.=E2=80=9D
Instead of expanding on Schempf=E2=80=99s point, Steckman offered an altern=
ative: =E2=80=9CMy view from the CRO perspective: the network effect to me =
is actually trust in Anduril.=E2=80=9D
Trust is critical to Anduril=E2=80=99s ambitions. Without it, Anduril won=
=E2=80=99t be able to weave Lattice OS into the fabric of defense, won=E2=
=80=99t be able to make its acquisitions pencil, won=E2=80=99t win large pr=
ograms, and won=E2=80=99t have a shot at fulfilling its mission: transformi=
ng US & allied military capabilities with advanced technology.=C2=A0
=C2=A0Building trust with the DoD requires a number of things.=C2=A0
First, it requires a deep understanding of DoD=E2=80=99s needs. As Steckman=
 explained to me, even the seemingly simple question of =E2=80=9CIs it the =
right tech?=E2=80=9D is not a simple one. =E2=80=9CIf you=E2=80=99re not fu=
lly informed, you might think something is a solve where it isn=E2=80=99t,=
=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9COften, the government isn=E2=80=99t buying a pi=
ece of new technology because it doesn=E2=80=99t solve the problem.=E2=80=
=9D
Getting to the point where you can develop a deep understanding is challeng=
ing in its own right. It means that the company needs to earn the right to =
see certain information, which means building up internal teams, technology=
, and processes to handle the security apparatus around sensitive informati=
on. It means being in Washington, DC and thoughtfully engaging with the com=
munity at the Pentagon or on Capitol Hill. It means understanding the curre=
nt set of equipment, hardware, and software that exist so you know where th=
e holes are and what you=E2=80=99ll need to integrate with.=C2=A0
Plus, there=E2=80=99s a paradox at play: you have to have a history of work=
ing with the DoD to be able to sell to them in the first place. While DoD h=
as tried to fix this by introducing startup-friendly programs like Small Bu=
siness Innovation Research (SBIR) and Small Business Technology Transfer (S=
TTR) and the Defense Innovation Unit=E2=80=99s Commercial Solutions Opening=
s, among others, needing to go through these first can represent a speed bu=
mp that prevents small businesses from selling into large programs.=C2=A0
Even then, the DoD is rightfully concerned about the health of the supplier=
s it buys from. It needs to feel confident that the company will be around =
to continue to supply the capabilities it=E2=80=99s contracted to supply. H=
ere, the $2.3 billion Anduril has raised from top-tier venture funds like F=
ounders Fund, a16z, Lux Capital, Thrive Capital, Valor Equity Partners, and=
 8VC helps.=C2=A0=C2=A0
If you overcome all of that, you still have to show that your technology ca=
n integrate with the hodgepodge of current and future systems that all of t=
he other pieces of technology that DoD acquires and operates, all of which =
have varying degrees of software sophistication, and most of which speak di=
fferent languages. Integrating with old or poorly written software of any k=
ind is difficult =E2=80=93 I remember months=E2=80=99 long projects at Brea=
ther when we had to integrate with outdated building management systems, an=
d that the engineers absolutely hated them =E2=80=93 but it=E2=80=99s even =
more challenging when the stakes are so high.=C2=A0
This gets to a core Anduril thesis: all incumbent defense companies are bui=
lt around hardware platforms and treat software as an afterthought. But the=
 company believes that approach is fighting the last war. For the wars of t=
he future, according to Anduril, you need to start with a software platform=
 that speaks to all sorts of hardware, and plug new hardware into that netw=
ork as it emerges.=C2=A0
This is where Lattice comes in. Lattice is the software network at the hear=
t of everything that Anduril does. Its first product, Lattice for Command a=
nd Control [ https://substack.com/redirect/37c12abc-13a7-46a7-83ed-7cd0526b=
da08?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =
is designed to accelerate the =E2=80=9Ckill chain=E2=80=9D by giving human =
operators information and interfaces designed to help them understand, deci=
de, and act more quickly. Lattice for Mission Autonomy [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/255f0ebf-5990-40b4-9cb4-80438bcced81?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], released in May [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/0d42d4ad-4146-46ba-b029-53660d7574ff?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], is built to allow =E2=80=
=9Ca single human to control and coordinate a wide range of autonomous asse=
ts across the ocean, land, and sky.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Lattice is designed to work with Anduril=E2=80=99s own hardware and to inte=
grate with hardware and platforms built by other vendors. In an ideal world=
, military personnel use Lattice to coordinate all of their missions, consu=
me synthesized information from sensors on every piece of hardware availabl=
e, command fleets of autonomous machines, and make decisions out of harm=E2=
=80=99s way. But getting to that point takes trust.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWe first proved the concept on missions like border security and a=
ir defense,=E2=80=9D Schimpf says in the video above, =E2=80=9Cand today, L=
attice is now automating the operations of hundreds of robotic systems depl=
oyed in tactical environments around the world.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That approach is built to design trust. Start with lower stakes missions, p=
rove not only that Lattice works but that it delivers better capabilities, =
and then repeat on increasingly high-stakes missions.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThe more government users see it working and delivering 2x, 3x, 10=
x capability, the more other government users will look at it and say, =E2=
=80=98I want it to do that for me=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Steckman explained. =E2=
=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s the flywheel: the more it=E2=80=99s out there and work=
ing, the more you get this interesting social effect on trust.=E2=80=9D
To build the software-like network effect that Schimpf and Thompson discuss=
ed, Anduril first needs the social network effect, the trust among customer=
s, operators, and other vendors that Lattice can deliver better outcomes.=
=C2=A0
But Lattice itself is just one piece of the company-level Anduril OS: the r=
elationships, security apparatus, knowledge, engagement, and software that =
build trust with DoD and put the company in a position to win competitions =
as they come up.=C2=A0
As Anduril OS continues to get stronger with time and experience, so too do=
es the company=E2=80=99s ability to sell advanced technologies =E2=80=93 th=
e apps on Anduril OS in this metaphor =E2=80=93 to US and allied militaries=
=2E As its flurry of acquisitions sho=
ws, the company seems to believe it=E2=
=80=99s now in a place where it can use Anduril OS as the bridge between th=
e defense tech free market and the DoD=E2=80=99s PPBE.=C2=A0
Anduril=E2=80=99s Acquisitions=C2=A0
I told you that this is a piece specifically on Anduril=E2=80=99s M&A strat=
egy, and then I spent seven pages talking about the defense industry and ho=
w Anduril is building trust with its customers. That, I think, was necessar=
y context.=C2=A0
Anduril is in a position to acquire companies because it=E2=80=99s built up=
 the hard-earned ability to sell their products to DoD better than the comp=
anies themselves could, and it has to acquire companies because of how the =
defense industry works.=C2=A0
Specifically, acquiring companies allows Anduril to sell into competitions =
