0; position: relative;"><strong>Defense is Weird</strong></h3><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">&#8220;Defense is weird.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64=
, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">When I aske=
d Adam Porter-Price, Anduril&#8217;s Head of Corporate Development and M&am=
p;A, and Matthew Steckman, its Chief Revenue Officer, in separate conversat=
ions, why Anduril acquires companies, they both gave the same response.&#16=
0;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">So what makes defense weird?&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;"><span>In Christian Brose&#8217;s recent Hoover Institute paper, </span=
><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/415b2910-923b-4dc2-8a39-4dccf1439=
cf0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=
 style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">Moneyball Mi=
litary</a><span>, he describes the core weirdness at the heart of defense: =
the Planning, Programming, Budgeting, and Execution (PPBE) system that the =
DoD uses to define the &#8220;military capabilities the nation requires and=
 how to validate, fund, and ultimately procure them.&#8221; Brose writes (e=
mphasis mine):</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e=
9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><s=
pan>The goal of the PPBE system, when Secretary of Defense Robert McNamara =
institutionalized it fully from 1961 to 1968, was not to optimize or better=
 manage capitalism in matters of national defense. It was to transcend capi=
talism altogether. </span><strong>It was an attempt to graft an allegedly s=
uperior, explicitly Soviet-style institution onto the postwar American gove=
rnment, ironically for the purpose of competing more effectively against th=
at Soviet adversary.</strong><span>&#160;</span></em></p><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; m=
argin-left: 20px;"><em><span>As Lofgren writes, &#8220;It was not hyperbole=
 when historian Charles Ries described military staff planning in 1964 to b=
e &#8216;</span><strong>almost socialist in its metaphysics</strong><span>.=
&#8217;&#8221; After all, &#8220;the economic expert and socialist alike be=
lieved that central planning could far outstrip the productive capability o=
f uncoordinated markets.&#8221;&#160;</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Let that sink in. It&#8217;s certainly not something I appreciate=
d. As the US faces threats from two centrally-planned economies, China and =
Russia, we&#8217;re doing so with a system modeled on theirs instead of lea=
ning into our capitalist advantage.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">To fix that, Brose=
 recommends splitting procurement in two: continue to use PPBE for traditio=
nal platforms and weapon systems, while establishing the Moneyball Military=
, generated through market creation, for &#8220;robotic vehicles of all siz=
es in all domains, constellations of small communications and intelligence =
satellites, and other commercially derived military systems.&#8221;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;">While there&#8217;s growing support for something like Brose&=
#8217;s proposal among America&#8217;s military leadership, the DoD is a ve=
ry large, slow-to-turn institution. So in the interim, Anduril wants to ser=
ve as the bridge between the two approaches. It needs to play by the rules =
of the PPBE on behalf of smaller defense tech companies, like an API into D=
oD.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">So what are the rules? Three are most releva=
nt to understanding Anduril&#8217;s acquisitions:</p><ol style=3D"margin-to=
p: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizi=
ng: border-box; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Small Number of B=
uyers</strong><span>. The defense sector is a </span><a href=3D"https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/71adaa64-6148-45f3-be60-7538b2198eb2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64=
, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">monopsony</a><span>, the demand-sid=
e version of a monopoly in which a market in which one buyer is the major p=
urchaser. Technically, a Prime may have 10-20 relationships across the DoD&=
#8217;s branches and agencies, and among its allies, but that&#8217;s a tin=
y number compared to a typical company&#8217;s client roster, and DoD sets =
the tone. Most of the spend they compete for comes out of the Congressional=
