developing its product for nearly four years at the time of acquisition, an=
d could get to market quickly.&#160;</span></p></li></ul><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">=
Porter-Price told me that Dive had done a lot of clever things from the har=
dware side, that its Dive-LD was good for the type of mission the US and it=
s allies want to perform, and that there was &#8220;nothing like it in the =
market.&#8221; At the same time, Dive wasn&#8217;t ready to win large contr=
acts on its own yet. Its autonomy software and ability to collaborate with =
other equipment in the water was far less developed than the hardware.&#160=
;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">So Anduril didn&#8217;t have a hardware product to s=
ell against a capability it knew allied militaries would need, and Dive did=
, but didn&#8217;t have the ability to sell into military buyers or the sof=
tware to deliver on its targeted autonomous capabilities.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">&#8220;Dive would have gotten there,&#8221; Porter-Price said, &#=
8220;but we sped up their timeline by 7-10 years.&#8221; On the flip side, =
Dive accelerated Anduril&#8217;s entry into a market where &#8220;customers=
 are banging down the door.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, =
64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Anduril=
 acquired Dive, turned it into Anduril Maritime, and made Dive Founder &amp=
; CEO Bill Lebo its GM. Within three months of the acquisition, the combine=
d team hooked the Dive-LD into Lattice, came up with a plan for turning the=
 pickup-truck-sized submarine into a school bus-sized version, and </span><=
